data.text:
Actor / Tribute to Michael Caine

Born on March 14, 1933, in London. After completing his military service, he works in regional theater in the early 50’s and makes his his film debut in A HILL IN KOREA in 1956. He breaks through in the 60’s with starring roles in a number of British films. After his starring role in ZULU, he portrays a spy in THE IPCRESS FILE and a ladies’ man in ALFIE. The film helps introduce him to American audiences and brings him his first Academy Award nomination. He gets his first Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor for Woody Allen’s HANNAH AND HER SISTERS, and his second one in 1999 for Lasse Hallström’s THE CIDER HOUSE RULES. In 2000, Queen Elizabeth grants him a knighthood. Caine has published two volumes of memoirs, “What’s It All About?” and “The Elephant to Hollywood”.
